    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. i turned the breaker off so it should be safe now. if i open the panel and look at the capacitor, what exactly am i looking for to see if it's blown? like is there a specific sign or smell?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A blown capacitor usually has bulging or leaking wax (often white or amber) around the canister, or it may appear physically damaged with a cracked plastic housing. You should also look for blackening around the terminals, which indicates electrical arcing and shorting. Even with the breaker off, do not touch the terminals or the canister directly, as high voltage can remain trapped inside, and the parts can become razor-sharp if they burst. If you see any of these signs, take the unit back to a professional rather than attempting a fix.",
